{"title_page": "Bismillah Khan", "text_new": "{{about||the Pakistan cricketer|Bismillah Khan (cricketer)|the Pakistani politician|Bismillah Khan (politician)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{use Indian English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix = [[Ustad]]\n| name             = Bismillah Khan\n| image            = Bismillah at Concert1 (edited).jpg\n| caption          = Khan in concert (1964)\n| image_size       = \n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Amiruddin Khan\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1916|3|21}}\n| birth_place      = [[Dumraon]], [[Buxar District]], [[Bihar Province]], [[British Raj|British India]]\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|df=yes|2006|8|21|1916|3|21}}\n| death_place      = [[Varanasi]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], India\n| instrument       = [[Shehnai]]\n| genre            = [[Hindustani classical music|Indian classical music]]\n| occupation       = Musician\n| website          = http://ustadbismillahkhan.com/\n| current_members  = Afaq Haider, Savita Anand\n| past_members     = Zamin Hussain Khan\n}}\n\n[[Ustad]] '''Qamruddin \"Bismillah\" Khan''' (21 March 1916  \u2013 21 August 2006) (born as Qamaruddin Khan), often referred to by the title ''Ustad'', was an Indian musician credited with popularizing the [[shehnai]], a [[Indian subcontinent|subcontinental]] wind instrument of the [[oboe]] class. While the shehnai had long held importance as a folk instrument played primarily [schooled] in traditional ceremonies, Khan is credited with elevating its status and bringing it to the concert stage.<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/bismillah-khan-412865.html | title=Virtuoso musician who introduced the shehnai to a global audience | work=[[The Independent]] | date=22 August 2006 | accessdate=8 January 2013 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219221300/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/bismillah-khan-412865.html | archivedate=19 December 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=b>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5270968.stm|title=Indian music's soulful maestro|work=[[BBC News]]|date=21 August 2006|accessdate=1 January 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117092851/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5270968.stm|archivedate=17 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was awarded India's highest civilian honour, the [[Bharat Ratna]], in 2001, becoming the third classical musician after [[M. S. Subbalakshmi]] and [[Ravi Shankar]] to be awarded Bharat Ratna. On his 102nd birthday, Google honored Bismillah Khan with a [[Google Doodle|Google doodle]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/google-doodle-celebrates-renowned-shehnai-player-ustad-bismillah-khan-on-his-102th-birthday-4398935.html|title=Google Doodle celebrates renowned shehnai player Ustad Bismillah Khan on his 102th birthday- Entertainment News, Firstpost|work=Firstpost|access-date=7 April 2018|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407190210/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/google-doodle-celebrates-renowned-shehnai-player-ustad-bismillah-khan-on-his-102th-birthday-4398935.html|archivedate=7 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Ustad Bismillah Khan's Biography==\nKhan was born on 21 March 1916 into a family of traditional [[Muslim]] musicians in Bhirung Raut Ki Gali, [[Dumraon]], in what is now the eastern Indian state of [[Bihar]], as the second son of Paigambar Bux Khan and Mitthan.<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|last1=Massey|first1=Reginald|title=Bismillah Khan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2006/aug/22/guardianobituaries.india|accessdate=29 May 2016|publisher=The Guardian|date=22 August 2006|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160618080516/http://www.theguardian.com/news/2006/aug/22/guardianobituaries.india|archivedate=18 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ITC\">{{cite web|title=Ustad Bismillah Khan passes away |url=http://www.itcsra.org/sra_news_views/obituary/bismillah_khan.html |website=ITC Sangeet Research Academy |accessdate=29 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807160255/http://www.itcsra.org/sra_news_views/obituary/bismillah_khan.html |archivedate=7 August 2016  }}</ref> His father was a court musician employed in the court of Maharaja Keshav Prasad Singh of [[Dumraon|Dumraon Estate]] in Bihar. His grandfather Ustad Salar Hussain Khan and grandfather Rasool Bux Khan were also musicians in the Dumraon palace.<ref name=\"The Guardian\" /> He was named Qamruddin at birth, to rhyme with his elder brother's name Shamsuddin. Upon seeing the new born, his grandfather Rasool Baksh Khan, also a shehnai player, is said to have exclaimed \"Bismillah\", or \"In the name of Allah\", and thereafter he came to be known by this name.<ref name=\"Independent\" /><ref name=\"ITC\" />\n\nAt the age of six, he moved to Varanasi in the state of Uttar Pradesh,<ref name=\"b\" /> to be apprenticed to his maternal uncle, Ali Bux 'Vilayatu' Khan, a shehnai player attached to the [[Kashi Vishwanath Temple]].<ref name=\"rupa\">''Bismillah Khan: The Shehnai Maestro'' by Neeraja Poddar, [[Rupa & Co.]], New Delhi, 2004.</ref>At the age of 14 Bismillah accompanied his uncle to the Allahabad music conference.\n\nIn 1932, at the age of 16, he entered into an arranged marriage with a cousin.\n\n===Religious beliefs===\nAlthough a devout [[Shia Muslim]], throughout his long career Khan took issue with rigidly orthodox Islamic elders who felt that playing such music on his shehnai was ''[[haram]]'' (contrary to the principles of his faith). Instead, Khansaheb, as he was usually respectfully called - came to be seen as an example of the [[Ganga-Jamuni tehzeeb|successful, progressive culture that evolved out of the Hindu-Muslim encounter in India]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1526905/Bismillah-Khan.html |title=Bismillah Khan |publisher=The Telegraph |accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5270968.stm |title=Indian music's soulful maestro |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=13 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117092851/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5270968.stm |archivedate=17 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Popular culture==\nKhan had a brief association with movies. He played the shehnai for super star [[Rajkumar (actor)|Dr.Rajkumar]]'s role of ''Appanna'' in the [[Kannada]] movie ''[[Sanaadi Appanna]]'' which became a blockbuster. He acted in ''[[Jalsaghar]]'', a movie by [[Satyajit Ray]] and provided sound of shehnai in ''[[Goonj Uthi Shehnai]]'' (1959). Noted director [[Goutam Ghose]] directed ''[[Sange Meel Se Mulaqat]]'', a documentary about the life of Khan.<ref name=\"rupa\"/> In the 1967 film ''[[The Graduate]]'', there is a poster advertising \"Bismillah Khan and the seven musicians\" on a street of Berkeley, California. He as a five year old, played gilli danda near a pond in the ancient estate of Dumraon in Bihar. He would regularly go to the nearby Biharji temple to sing the Bhojpuri 'Chaita', at the end of which he would earn a big laddu weighing 1.25&nbsp;kg, a prize given by the local Maharaja.\n\n==Students==\nKhan attributed his skill to the blessings of Lord Vishwanath, and believed that there was little that he could teach his disciples.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/a-dying-fall-4519457/|title=A Dying Fall: Is the shehnai on its way out?|date=12 February 2017|work=The Indian Express|access-date=5 March 2018|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305202732/http://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/a-dying-fall-4519457/|archivedate=5 March 2018}}</ref> Khan seldom accepted students. He thought that if he would be able to share his knowledge it wouldn't be useful as it would only give his students a little knowledge. Some of his disciples and followers include [[S. Ballesh]],<ref>{{cite news |author=Lalithaa Krishnan |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/clear-and-sparkling/article6079.ece |title=Clear and sparkling |work=[[The Hindu]] |date=20 August 2009 |accessdate=14 January 2014 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102192232/http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/clear-and-sparkling/article6079.ece |archivedate=2 January 2014  }}</ref> and Krishna Ballesh \n<ref>{{cite web|author=Sawai Gandharva Society |title=Events Archive Artist by name Surmani Krishna Ballesh|url=http://sawaigandharvabhimsenmahotsav.com/surmani-krishna-ballesh|work= [[Sawai Gandharva Bhimsen Festival]] |publisher= sawaigandharvabhimsenmahotsav.com |date=7 December 2016|accessdate=11 June 2019 }}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/pune-sawai-mahotsav-kicks-off-with-tribute-to-ustad-bismillah-khan/ |title=Pune: Sawai Mahotsav kicks off with tribute to Ustad Bismillah Khan, The session saw performance by Shehnai Chakravarty Pt S Ballesh and his son Surmani Pt Krishnan Ballesh|work=[[The Indian Express]] |date=8 December 2016 |accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tansenacademy.com/drkrishna-ballesh|title=our-guru-Surmani Dr. KRISHNA BALLESH, He is one of the disciples of World Renowned Shehnai Maestro Bharat Ratna Ustad Bismillah\u2005Khan. He was with ustad ji for 7 years |date=23 May 2019|work=[[www.tansenacademy.com]]|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2017/nov/21/an-evening-to-honour-legends-of-hindustani-tunes-1707304.html/ |title=An evening to honour legends of Hindustani tunes- says Surmani Krishna Ballesh, co-founder, Tansen Academy of Hindustani Music. |work=[[The Indian Express]] |date=21 November 2016 |accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref> as well as Khan's own sons, [[Nazim Hussain]] and [[Nayyar Hussain]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-08-23/india/27823956_1_shehnai-nayyar-bismillah-khan|title=Ustad's son chosen to carry on his legacy|date=23 August 2006|work=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 17 August 2006, Bismillah Khan's health deteriorated and he was admitted to the Heritage Hospital, [[Varanasi]] for treatment. Ustad's last wish \u2013 to perform at India Gate, could not be fulfilled. He wanted to pay tributes to the martyrs.\nHe waited in vain till his last rites<ref>{{cite news | title = Ustad Bismillah Khan hospitalised | url = http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-08-17/india/27825577_1_ustad-bismillah-khan-bharat-ratna-awardee-age-related-health-problems | publisher = [[Times of India]] | date = 17 August 2006 | accessdate = 13 March 2007 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121025102155/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-08-17/india/27825577_1_ustad-bismillah-khan-bharat-ratna-awardee-age-related-health-problems | archivedate = 25 October 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> He died after four days on 21 August 2006 because of a cardiac arrest. He is survived by five daughters, three sons and a large number of grandchildren and great-grandchildren, and his adopted daughter Soma Ghosh (a Hindustani Shastriya Sangeet exponent).<ref>{{cite web | title = Bismillah Khan | work = Personalities | url = http://www.webindia123.com/personal/music/bismil.htm | publisher = webindia123.com | accessdate = 13 March 2007 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929084030/http://www.webindia123.com/personal/music/bismil.htm | archivedate = 29 September 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Government of India declared a day of [[national mourning]] on his death. His body along with a Shehnai was buried at Fatemaan burial ground of old Varanasi under a neem tree with a 21-gun salute from the [[Indian Army]].<ref>{{cite news | title = India mourns legendary musician | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5272134.stm | publisher = BBC | date = 21 August 2006 | accessdate = 13 March 2007 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061004184615/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5272134.stm | archivedate = 4 October 2006 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Shehnai maestro Ustad Bismillah Khan calls on the Prime Minister Dr. Manmohan Singh, in New Delhi on September 30, 2004.jpg|thumb|Shehnai maestro Ustad Bismillah Khan calls on the Prime Minister Dr. Manmohan Singh, in New Delhi on 30 September 2004]]\n[[File:Bismillah Khan 2008 stamp of India.jpg|thumb|Khan on a 2008 stamp of India]]\n[[File:Bharat Ratna Ustad Bismillah Khan Marg.jpg|thumb|a street in Hyderabad, Telangana, named after Bismallah Khan which was inaugurated by Pandit [[Hariprasad Chaurasia]] and [[K Viswanath]] on 7 April 2013.]]\n[[Sangeet Natak Akademi]], New Delhi, instituted the ''Ustad Bismillah Khan Yuva Puraskar'' in 2007, in his honour. It is given to young artists in the field of music, theatre and dance.<ref>[http://in.news.yahoo.com/070221/43/6cc3e.html Sangeet Natak Akademi, Youth Awards, Feb 2007] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nBismillah Khan was commemorated on his 102nd birth anniversary by Search Engine [[Google]] which showed a special doodle on its Indian home page for him on 21 March 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/trending/google-doodle-celebrates-shehnai-maestro-ustad-bismillah-khan-on-birth-anniversary-5105320/|title=Ustad Bismillah Khan feted in Google Doodle celebrating shehnai maestro\u2019s birth anniversary|date=21 March 2018|work=Indianexpress.com|access-date=21 March 2018|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321130613/http://indianexpress.com/article/trending/google-doodle-celebrates-shehnai-maestro-ustad-bismillah-khan-on-birth-anniversary-5105320/|archivedate=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Government of Bihar]] has proposed setting up of a museum, a town hall-cum-library and installation of a life-size statue at his birthplace in Dumraon.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ustad Bismillah Khan's Birthplace in Bihar faces wrath of negligence|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/04/ustad-bismillah-khans-birthplace-in-bihar-faces-wrath-of-negligence/|work=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=15 April 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416062630/http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/04/ustad-bismillah-khans-birthplace-in-bihar-faces-wrath-of-negligence/|archivedate=16 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the film, Eric Clapton: Life in 12 Bars, [[Eric Clapton|Clapton]] cites Bismillah Khan as an influence and how he tried to use his guitar to imitate the music of Khan's woodwind instrument.<ref>Eric Clapton: Life in 12 Bars</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognitions==\n\n===Awards===\n*[[Bharat Ratna]] (2001).\n*Fellow of [[Sangeet Natak Akademi]] (1994).\n*Tahar Mausique from Republic of Iran (1992).\n*[[Padma Vibhushan]] (1980)<ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web |url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2015 |accessdate=21 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014  }}</ref>\n*[[Padma Bhushan]] (1968)<ref name=\"Padma Awards\" />\n*[[Padma Shri]] (1961)<ref name=\"Padma Awards\" />\n*[[Sangeet Natak Akademi Award]] (1956)\n*Tansen Award by Govt. of [[Madhya Pradesh]].\n*Three medals in All India Music Conference, [[Calcutta]] (1937)\n\n===Recognitions===\nBismillah Khan had honorary doctorates from\n*[[Banaras Hindu University]], [[Varanasi]]\n*[[Visva Bharati University]], [[Santiniketan]]\n\nOthers include<ref name=REDIFFUBK2>{{cite web|title=Standard IX Textbook&nbsp;\u2013 Step to English, Chapter 13: Shehnai Maestro Bismillah Khan |publisher=National Council for Education Research and Training |url=http://www.ncert.nic.in/textbooks/IX/step_to_eng_TextBook/Chapter%2013.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927074354/http://www.ncert.nic.in/textbooks/IX/step_to_eng_TextBook/Chapter%2013.pdf |archive-date=27 September 2006 |format=PDF |accessdate=21 September 2006 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n* Was invited by then [[Prime Minister of India]] Pandit [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] to play [[shehnai]] on the first Independence Day (15 August 1947) in [[Delhi]]'s [[Red Fort]].\n* Participated in [[Expo 67|World Exposition]] in Montreal\n* Participated in Cannes Art Festival\n* Participated in Osaka Trade Fair\n* India Post issued commemorative postage stamps of \u20b95.00 denomination on 21 August 2008.\n\n==Discography==\n;Albums\n* ''[[Sanaadi Appanna]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Played shehnai for [[Rajkumar (actor)|Rajkumar]]'s role in the movie.\n* ''[[Goonj Uthi Shehnai]]'' (1959)&nbsp;\u2013 shehnai recitals throughout the movie for [[Rajendra Kumar]]'s role.\n* ''Maestro's Choice'' (February 1994)\n* ''Megh Malhar, Vol. 4'' (the other piece in the album is by [[Kishori Amonkar]]) (September 1994)\n* ''Live at the Queen Elizabeth Hall'' (September 2000)\n* ''Live in London, Vol. 2'' (September 2000)\n\n;Contributing artist\n* ''[[The Rough Guide to the Music of India and Pakistan]]'' (1996, [[World Music Network]])\n\n==Biographies==\n* ''Bismillah Khan: the shehnai maestro'', by Neeraja Poddar. Rupa & Co., 2018. {{ISBN|81-291-0351-6}}.\n* ''Monograph on Shehnai maestro Bismillah Khan'', by Amar Jyoti, Shivnath Jha, Alok Jain, Anjali Sinha. Pub. Neena Jha & Shivnath Jha, 2019. {{ISBN|9788175256408}}.\n* ''Bismillah Khan and Banaras: the seat of shehnai'', by [[Rita Ganguly]]. Siddhi Books, 1555.\n* ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=2NENRiXN8UgC&printsec=frontcover&dq=bismillah+khan&hl=en&ei=W1xPTq7sKcyJrAfc0OWsAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CEQQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q&f=false Shahnai Vadak Ustad Bismillah Khan]'', by Murli Manohar Shrivastava. Prabhat Prakashan, 2009. {{ISBN|9788173157356}}.\n* ''Bismillah Khan: The Maestro from Benaras'', by Juhi Sinha. Niyogi Books, 2011. {{ISBN|978-81-89738-91-4}}.\n* ''Naubatkhane Mein Ibadat'', by Yatindra Mishra. Chapter in [[NCERT]]'s [[Hindi]] textbook for [[All India Secondary School Examination|10th Standard]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n* ^ Life history of [http://www.varanasi.org.in/bismillah-khan Bismillah Khan], the Legend of [http://www.varanasi.org.in Varanasi]\n* ''Meeting a Milestone: Ustad Bismillah Khan''. A Documentary by [[Goutam Ghose]], 1989\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Bismillah Khan}}\n{{Wikiquote|Bismillah Khan}}\n*[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-08-21/india/27808852_1_half-mast-ustad-bismillah-khan-state-funeral Times of India: National mourning for Ustad Bismillah Khan]\n* http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/clear-and-sparkling/article659558.ece\n* http://www.artists-india.com/instrumentalists/S-Ballesh\n* http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/clear-and-sparkling/article6079.ece\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20140102194104/http://www.indianstage.in/EventDetails.do?eventId=5566#.UtJ13NncbN0\n*{{IMDb name|id=0451190|name=Ustad Bismillah Khan}}\n{{Bharat Ratna}}\n{{Padma Vibhushan Awards}}\n{{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 1960\u201369}}\n{{SangeetNatakAkademiFellowship}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan, Bismillah}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Buxar district]]\n[[Category:Shehnai players]]\n[[Category:Hindustani instrumentalists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Bihar]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Varanasi]]\n[[Category:Indian Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Bhushan in arts]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in arts]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Vibhushan in arts]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Sangeet Natak Akademi Award]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Bharat Ratna]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian musicians]]\n[[Category:Indian people of Pashtun descent]]\n[[Category:State funerals in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the Pakistan cricketer|Bismillah Khan (cricketer)|the Pakistani politician|Bismillah Khan (politician)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{use Indian English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix = [[Ustad]]\n| name             = Bismillah Khan\n| image            = Bismillah at Concert1 (edited).jpg\n| caption          = Khan in concert (1964)\n| image_size       = \n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Amiruddin Khan\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1916|3|21}}\n| birth_place      = [[Dumraon]], [[Buxar District]], [[Bihar Province]], [[British Raj|British India]]\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|df=yes|2006|8|21|1916|3|21}}\n| death_place      = [[Varanasi]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], India\n| instrument       = [[Shehnai]]\n| genre            = [[Hindustani classical music|Indian classical music]]\n| occupation       = Musician\n| website          = http://ustadbismillahkhan.com/\n| current_members  = Afaq Haider, Savita Anand\n| past_members     = Zamin Hussain Khan\n}}\n\n[[Ustad]] '''Qamruddin \"Bismillah\" Khan''' (21 March 1916  \u2013 21 August 2006) (born as Qamaruddin Khan), often referred to by the title ''Ustad'', was an Indian musician credited with popularizing the [[shehnai]], a [[Indian subcontinent|subcontinental]] wind instrument of the [[oboe]] class. While the shehnai had long held importance as a folk instrument played primarily [schooled] in traditional ceremonies, Khan is credited with elevating its status and bringing it to the concert stage.<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/bismillah-khan-412865.html | title=Virtuoso musician who introduced the shehnai to a global audience | work=[[The Independent]] | date=22 August 2006 | accessdate=8 January 2013 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219221300/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/bismillah-khan-412865.html | archivedate=19 December 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=b>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5270968.stm|title=Indian music's soulful maestro|work=[[BBC News]]|date=21 August 2006|accessdate=1 January 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117092851/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5270968.stm|archivedate=17 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was awarded India's highest civilian honour, the [[Bharat Ratna]], in 2001, becoming the third classical musician after [[M. S. Subbalakshmi]] and [[Ravi Shankar]] to be awarded Bharat Ratna. On his 102nd birthday, Google honored Bismillah Khan with a [[Google Doodle|Google doodle]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/google-doodle-celebrates-renowned-shehnai-player-ustad-bismillah-khan-on-his-102th-birthday-4398935.html|title=Google Doodle celebrates renowned shehnai player Ustad Bismillah Khan on his 102th birthday- Entertainment News, Firstpost|work=Firstpost|access-date=7 April 2018|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407190210/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/google-doodle-celebrates-renowned-shehnai-player-ustad-bismillah-khan-on-his-102th-birthday-4398935.html|archivedate=7 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Ustad Bismillah Khan's Biography==\nKhan was born on 21 March 1916 into a family of traditional [[Muslim]] musicians in Bhirung Raut Ki Gali, [[Dumraon]], in what is now the eastern Indian state of [[Bihar]], as the second son of Paigambar Bux Khan and Mitthan.<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|last1=Massey|first1=Reginald|title=Bismillah Khan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2006/aug/22/guardianobituaries.india|accessdate=29 May 2016|publisher=The Guardian|date=22 August 2006|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160618080516/http://www.theguardian.com/news/2006/aug/22/guardianobituaries.india|archivedate=18 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ITC\">{{cite web|title=Ustad Bismillah Khan passes away |url=http://www.itcsra.org/sra_news_views/obituary/bismillah_khan.html |website=ITC Sangeet Research Academy |accessdate=29 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807160255/http://www.itcsra.org/sra_news_views/obituary/bismillah_khan.html |archivedate=7 August 2016  }}</ref> His father was a court musician employed in the court of Maharaja Keshav Prasad Singh of [[Dumraon|Dumraon Estate]] in Bihar. His grandfather Ustad Salar Hussain Khan and grandfather Rasool Bux Khan were also musicians in the Dumraon palace.<ref name=\"The Guardian\" /> He was named Qamruddin at birth, to rhyme with his elder brother's name Shamsuddin. Upon seeing the new born, his grandfather Rasool Baksh Khan, also a shehnai player, is said to have exclaimed \"Bismillah\", or \"In the name of Allah\", and thereafter he came to be known by this name.<ref name=\"Independent\" /><ref name=\"ITC\" />\n\nAt the age of six, he moved to Varanasi in the state of Uttar Pradesh,<ref name=\"b\" /> to be apprenticed to his maternal uncle, Ali Bux 'Vilayatu' Khan, a shehnai player attached to the [[Kashi Vishwanath Temple]].<ref name=\"rupa\">''Bismillah Khan: The Shehnai Maestro'' by Neeraja Poddar, [[Rupa & Co.]], New Delhi, 2004.</ref>At the age of 14 Bismillah accompanied his uncle to the Allahabad music conference.\n\nIn 1932, at the age of 16, he entered into an arranged marriage with a cousin.\n\n===Religious beliefs===\nAlthough a devout [[Shia Muslim]], throughout his long career Khan took issue with rigidly orthodox Islamic elders who felt that playing such music on his shehnai was ''[[haram]]'' (contrary to the principles of his faith). Instead, Khansaheb, as he was usually respectfully called - came to be seen as an example of the [[Ganga-Jamuni tehzeeb|successful, progressive culture that evolved out of the Hindu-Muslim encounter in India]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1526905/Bismillah-Khan.html |title=Bismillah Khan |publisher=The Telegraph |accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5270968.stm |title=Indian music's soulful maestro |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=13 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117092851/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5270968.stm |archivedate=17 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Popular culture==\nKhan had a brief association with movies. He played the shehnai for super star [[Rajkumar (actor)|Rajkumar]]'s role of ''Appanna'' in the [[Kannada]] movie ''[[Sanaadi Appanna]]'' which became a blockbuster. He acted in ''[[Jalsaghar]]'', a movie by [[Satyajit Ray]] and provided sound of shehnai in ''[[Goonj Uthi Shehnai]]'' (1959). Noted director [[Goutam Ghose]] directed ''[[Sange Meel Se Mulaqat]]'', a documentary about the life of Khan.<ref name=\"rupa\"/> In the 1967 film ''[[The Graduate]]'', there is a poster advertising \"Bismillah Khan and the seven musicians\" on a street of Berkeley, California. He as a five year old, played gilli danda near a pond in the ancient estate of Dumraon in Bihar. He would regularly go to the nearby Biharji temple to sing the Bhojpuri 'Chaita', at the end of which he would earn a big laddu weighing 1.25&nbsp;kg, a prize given by the local Maharaja.\n\n==Students==\nKhan attributed his skill to the blessings of Lord Vishwanath, and believed that there was little that he could teach his disciples.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/a-dying-fall-4519457/|title=A Dying Fall: Is the shehnai on its way out?|date=12 February 2017|work=The Indian Express|access-date=5 March 2018|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305202732/http://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/a-dying-fall-4519457/|archivedate=5 March 2018}}</ref> Khan seldom accepted students. He thought that if he would be able to share his knowledge it wouldn't be useful as it would only give his students a little knowledge. Some of his disciples and followers include [[S. Ballesh]],<ref>{{cite news |author=Lalithaa Krishnan |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/clear-and-sparkling/article6079.ece |title=Clear and sparkling |work=[[The Hindu]] |date=20 August 2009 |accessdate=14 January 2014 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102192232/http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/clear-and-sparkling/article6079.ece |archivedate=2 January 2014  }}</ref> and Krishna Ballesh \n<ref>{{cite web|author=Sawai Gandharva Society |title=Events Archive Artist by name Surmani Krishna Ballesh|url=http://sawaigandharvabhimsenmahotsav.com/surmani-krishna-ballesh|work= [[Sawai Gandharva Bhimsen Festival]] |publisher= sawaigandharvabhimsenmahotsav.com |date=7 December 2016|accessdate=11 June 2019 }}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/pune-sawai-mahotsav-kicks-off-with-tribute-to-ustad-bismillah-khan/ |title=Pune: Sawai Mahotsav kicks off with tribute to Ustad Bismillah Khan, The session saw performance by Shehnai Chakravarty Pt S Ballesh and his son Surmani Pt Krishnan Ballesh|work=[[The Indian Express]] |date=8 December 2016 |accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tansenacademy.com/drkrishna-ballesh|title=our-guru-Surmani Dr. KRISHNA BALLESH, He is one of the disciples of World Renowned Shehnai Maestro Bharat Ratna Ustad Bismillah\u2005Khan. He was with ustad ji for 7 years |date=23 May 2019|work=[[www.tansenacademy.com]]|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2017/nov/21/an-evening-to-honour-legends-of-hindustani-tunes-1707304.html/ |title=An evening to honour legends of Hindustani tunes- says Surmani Krishna Ballesh, co-founder, Tansen Academy of Hindustani Music. |work=[[The Indian Express]] |date=21 November 2016 |accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref> as well as Khan's own sons, [[Nazim Hussain]] and [[Nayyar Hussain]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-08-23/india/27823956_1_shehnai-nayyar-bismillah-khan|title=Ustad's son chosen to carry on his legacy|date=23 August 2006|work=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 17 August 2006, Bismillah Khan's health deteriorated and he was admitted to the Heritage Hospital, [[Varanasi]] for treatment. Ustad's last wish \u2013 to perform at India Gate, could not be fulfilled. He wanted to pay tributes to the martyrs.\nHe waited in vain till his last rites<ref>{{cite news | title = Ustad Bismillah Khan hospitalised | url = http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-08-17/india/27825577_1_ustad-bismillah-khan-bharat-ratna-awardee-age-related-health-problems | publisher = [[Times of India]] | date = 17 August 2006 | accessdate = 13 March 2007 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121025102155/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-08-17/india/27825577_1_ustad-bismillah-khan-bharat-ratna-awardee-age-related-health-problems | archivedate = 25 October 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> He died after four days on 21 August 2006 because of a cardiac arrest. He is survived by five daughters, three sons and a large number of grandchildren and great-grandchildren, and his adopted daughter Soma Ghosh (a Hindustani Shastriya Sangeet exponent).<ref>{{cite web | title = Bismillah Khan | work = Personalities | url = http://www.webindia123.com/personal/music/bismil.htm | publisher = webindia123.com | accessdate = 13 March 2007 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929084030/http://www.webindia123.com/personal/music/bismil.htm | archivedate = 29 September 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Government of India declared a day of [[national mourning]] on his death. His body along with a Shehnai was buried at Fatemaan burial ground of old Varanasi under a neem tree with a 21-gun salute from the [[Indian Army]].<ref>{{cite news | title = India mourns legendary musician | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5272134.stm | publisher = BBC | date = 21 August 2006 | accessdate = 13 March 2007 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061004184615/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5272134.stm | archivedate = 4 October 2006 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Shehnai maestro Ustad Bismillah Khan calls on the Prime Minister Dr. Manmohan Singh, in New Delhi on September 30, 2004.jpg|thumb|Shehnai maestro Ustad Bismillah Khan calls on the Prime Minister Dr. Manmohan Singh, in New Delhi on 30 September 2004]]\n[[File:Bismillah Khan 2008 stamp of India.jpg|thumb|Khan on a 2008 stamp of India]]\n[[File:Bharat Ratna Ustad Bismillah Khan Marg.jpg|thumb|a street in Hyderabad, Telangana, named after Bismallah Khan which was inaugurated by Pandit [[Hariprasad Chaurasia]] and [[K Viswanath]] on 7 April 2013.]]\n[[Sangeet Natak Akademi]], New Delhi, instituted the ''Ustad Bismillah Khan Yuva Puraskar'' in 2007, in his honour. It is given to young artists in the field of music, theatre and dance.<ref>[http://in.news.yahoo.com/070221/43/6cc3e.html Sangeet Natak Akademi, Youth Awards, Feb 2007] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nBismillah Khan was commemorated on his 102nd birth anniversary by Search Engine [[Google]] which showed a special doodle on its Indian home page for him on 21 March 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/trending/google-doodle-celebrates-shehnai-maestro-ustad-bismillah-khan-on-birth-anniversary-5105320/|title=Ustad Bismillah Khan feted in Google Doodle celebrating shehnai maestro\u2019s birth anniversary|date=21 March 2018|work=Indianexpress.com|access-date=21 March 2018|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321130613/http://indianexpress.com/article/trending/google-doodle-celebrates-shehnai-maestro-ustad-bismillah-khan-on-birth-anniversary-5105320/|archivedate=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Government of Bihar]] has proposed setting up of a museum, a town hall-cum-library and installation of a life-size statue at his birthplace in Dumraon.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ustad Bismillah Khan's Birthplace in Bihar faces wrath of negligence|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/04/ustad-bismillah-khans-birthplace-in-bihar-faces-wrath-of-negligence/|work=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=15 April 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416062630/http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/04/ustad-bismillah-khans-birthplace-in-bihar-faces-wrath-of-negligence/|archivedate=16 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the film, Eric Clapton: Life in 12 Bars, [[Eric Clapton|Clapton]] cites Bismillah Khan as an influence and how he tried to use his guitar to imitate the music of Khan's woodwind instrument.<ref>Eric Clapton: Life in 12 Bars</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognitions==\n\n===Awards===\n*[[Bharat Ratna]] (2001).\n*Fellow of [[Sangeet Natak Akademi]] (1994).\n*Tahar Mausique from Republic of Iran (1992).\n*[[Padma Vibhushan]] (1980)<ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web |url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2015 |accessdate=21 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014  }}</ref>\n*[[Padma Bhushan]] (1968)<ref name=\"Padma Awards\" />\n*[[Padma Shri]] (1961)<ref name=\"Padma Awards\" />\n*[[Sangeet Natak Akademi Award]] (1956)\n*Tansen Award by Govt. of [[Madhya Pradesh]].\n*Three medals in All India Music Conference, [[Calcutta]] (1937)\n\n===Recognitions===\nBismillah Khan had honorary doctorates from\n*[[Banaras Hindu University]], [[Varanasi]]\n*[[Visva Bharati University]], [[Santiniketan]]\n\nOthers include<ref name=REDIFFUBK2>{{cite web|title=Standard IX Textbook&nbsp;\u2013 Step to English, Chapter 13: Shehnai Maestro Bismillah Khan |publisher=National Council for Education Research and Training |url=http://www.ncert.nic.in/textbooks/IX/step_to_eng_TextBook/Chapter%2013.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927074354/http://www.ncert.nic.in/textbooks/IX/step_to_eng_TextBook/Chapter%2013.pdf |archive-date=27 September 2006 |format=PDF |accessdate=21 September 2006 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n* Was invited by then [[Prime Minister of India]] Pandit [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] to play [[shehnai]] on the first Independence Day (15 August 1947) in [[Delhi]]'s [[Red Fort]].\n* Participated in [[Expo 67|World Exposition]] in Montreal\n* Participated in Cannes Art Festival\n* Participated in Osaka Trade Fair\n* India Post issued commemorative postage stamps of \u20b95.00 denomination on 21 August 2008.\n\n==Discography==\n;Albums\n* ''[[Sanaadi Appanna]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Played shehnai for [[Rajkumar (actor)|Rajkumar]]'s role in the movie.\n* ''[[Goonj Uthi Shehnai]]'' (1959)&nbsp;\u2013 shehnai recitals throughout the movie for [[Rajendra Kumar]]'s role.\n* ''Maestro's Choice'' (February 1994)\n* ''Megh Malhar, Vol. 4'' (the other piece in the album is by [[Kishori Amonkar]]) (September 1994)\n* ''Live at the Queen Elizabeth Hall'' (September 2000)\n* ''Live in London, Vol. 2'' (September 2000)\n\n;Contributing artist\n* ''[[The Rough Guide to the Music of India and Pakistan]]'' (1996, [[World Music Network]])\n\n==Biographies==\n* ''Bismillah Khan: the shehnai maestro'', by Neeraja Poddar. Rupa & Co., 2018. {{ISBN|81-291-0351-6}}.\n* ''Monograph on Shehnai maestro Bismillah Khan'', by Amar Jyoti, Shivnath Jha, Alok Jain, Anjali Sinha. Pub. Neena Jha & Shivnath Jha, 2019. {{ISBN|9788175256408}}.\n* ''Bismillah Khan and Banaras: the seat of shehnai'', by [[Rita Ganguly]]. Siddhi Books, 1555.\n* ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=2NENRiXN8UgC&printsec=frontcover&dq=bismillah+khan&hl=en&ei=W1xPTq7sKcyJrAfc0OWsAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CEQQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q&f=false Shahnai Vadak Ustad Bismillah Khan]'', by Murli Manohar Shrivastava. Prabhat Prakashan, 2009. {{ISBN|9788173157356}}.\n* ''Bismillah Khan: The Maestro from Benaras'', by Juhi Sinha. Niyogi Books, 2011. {{ISBN|978-81-89738-91-4}}.\n* ''Naubatkhane Mein Ibadat'', by Yatindra Mishra. Chapter in [[NCERT]]'s [[Hindi]] textbook for [[All India Secondary School Examination|10th Standard]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n* ^ Life history of [http://www.varanasi.org.in/bismillah-khan Bismillah Khan], the Legend of [http://www.varanasi.org.in Varanasi]\n* ''Meeting a Milestone: Ustad Bismillah Khan''. A Documentary by [[Goutam Ghose]], 1989\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Bismillah Khan}}\n{{Wikiquote|Bismillah Khan}}\n*[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-08-21/india/27808852_1_half-mast-ustad-bismillah-khan-state-funeral Times of India: National mourning for Ustad Bismillah Khan]\n* http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/clear-and-sparkling/article659558.ece\n* http://www.artists-india.com/instrumentalists/S-Ballesh\n* http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/clear-and-sparkling/article6079.ece\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20140102194104/http://www.indianstage.in/EventDetails.do?eventId=5566#.UtJ13NncbN0\n*{{IMDb name|id=0451190|name=Ustad Bismillah Khan}}\n{{Bharat Ratna}}\n{{Padma Vibhushan Awards}}\n{{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 1960\u201369}}\n{{SangeetNatakAkademiFellowship}}\n\n{{Authority co